fields.name: Black coffee
fields.description: Black. Black coffee is as simple as it gets with ground coffee beans steeped in hot water, served warm

fields.name: Cappuccino
fields.description: A cappuccino contains equal parts of espresso, steamed and milk froth.

fields.name: Americano
fields.description: An Americano is therefore a black coffee â€” unless you add milk!

fields.name: Turkish delight coffee
fields.description: Turkish coffee is unique for its fine grind, special brewing method, and cultural significance.

fields.name: Doppio coffee
fields.description: Doppio espresso is a double shot which is extracted using double the amount of ground coffee in a larger-sized portafilter basket. This results in 60 ml of drink, double the amount of a single shot espresso.

fields.name: Expresso Coffee
fields.description: Espresso is a coffee-brewing method in which a small amount of nearly boiling water is forced under pressure through finely ground coffee beans.

fields.name: Irish Coffee
fields.description: Irish coffee is a caffeinated alcoholic drink consisting of Irish whiskey, hot coffee and sugar, which has been stirred and topped with cream. The coffee is drunk through the cream.

fields.name: Latte Coffee
fields.description: This espresso is then combined with several ounces of steamed milk to create a rich, creamy beverage that has a more subtle espresso taste. The typical ratio for espresso to steamed milk is about 1-to-2.

fields.name: Swedish Egg Coffee
fields.description: Traditional Swedish egg coffee is made by cracking an entire egg, including the shell, into a cup, mixing the egg with ground coffee, and then letting the mixture simmer on the stove. The idea is for the egg to remove impurities from the coffee, resulting in a smoother cup of coffee.
